tion.Key FeaturesGuides students through the novels they are required to read on Anglo Arab literature coursesLooks at authors including Ameen Rihani, Ahdaf Soueif, Waguih Ghali, Etel Adnan, Diana Abu-Jaber, Jamal Mahjoub, Rawi Hage, Loubna Haikal, Jad El Hage, Mohja Kahf, Samia Serageldin, Rabih Alameddine, Mona Simpson, and Leila Aboulela, Laila Lalami, Hisham Matar and Fadia FaqirTopics include pedagogy and the literary marketplace"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aEnglish literaturexArab authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAlami, Ahmed Idrissi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahab, F. Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGana, Nouri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartman, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHassan, Waïl S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayward, Maysa Abou-Youssef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoyt, Heather M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLayoun, Mary N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMicklethwait, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Lindsey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaaman, Mara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNash, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNikro, Saadi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNyman